doc.ContractDescription: RR LYRAE VARIABLE STARS ARE A COMPONENT OF THE COSMIC DISTANCE LADDER AND A CONTRIBUTOR TO THE INTEGRATED ULTRAVIOLET (UV) LIGHT OF UNRESOLVED EXTRAGALACTIC STELLAR POPULATIONS. HOWEVER, THERE HAVE BEEN FEW STUDIES MADE OF RR LYRAE STARS IN THE UV DESPITE THE LARGE (2-8 MAG) AMPLITUDES OF THEIR PULSATIONS IN THE UV AND THE INSIGHTS UV LIGHT CURVES COULD PROVIDE ON THE ASTROPHYSICS OF PULSATING STARS. A PRELIMINARY SWIFT/UVOT STUDY OF THE GLOBULAR CLUSTER M3 HAS SHOWN THAT SWIFT HAS AN OUTSTANDING CAPABILITY IN CONSTRAINING THE LIGHT CURVES OF RR LYRAE STARS IN THE NUV. WE NOW PROPOSE A COMPLETE AND SYSTEMATIC SURVEY OF TWO OF THE MOST RR LYRAE-RICH GLOBULAR CLUSTERS IN THE GALAXY. THIS SURVEY, DESIGNED FOR MINIMAL IMPACT ON SWIFT OPERATIONS, WILL PRODUCE THE FIRST LARGE CATALOG OF PRECISE UV LIGHT CURVES FOR RR LYRAE STARS, PROVIDING CRITICAL INSIGHT INTO THESE IMPORTANT STARS AND INTO THE UV PROPERTIES OF UNRESOLVED EXTRAGALACTIC STELLAR POPULATIONS.

doc.ContractDescription: KAYE TEMPERATURE REFERENCE SYSTEM DO NOT SEND TO CAL LAB DEAN KOCAN 216-433-2716 MS: 6-2 JONATHON PONDER 216-433-6258 MS: 6-2

ACTIVE GALACTIC NUCLEI (AGNS) ARE AMONG THE MOST EXTREME PHYSICAL ENVIRONMENTS IN THE UNIVERSE, AND IT NOW APPEARS THAT FEEDBACK FROM AGN WINDS AND JETS PLAYS A CRITICAL ROLE IN THE EVOLUTION OF TYPICAL MASSIVE GALAXIES AND LARGER-SCALE STRUCTURES. THE PART OF AGN SPECTRAL ENERGY DISTRIBUTIONS (SEDS) FROM THE X-RAY TO THE OPTICAL/UV IS WHERE THE BULK OF THE ACCRETION LUMINOSITY, CREATED BY THE ACCRETION DISK AND ITS CORONA, IS VISIBLE FOR OBJECTS WITHOUT SUBSTANTIAL OBSCURATION. THIS IS ALSO THE RADIATION THAT DRIVES AGN WINDS AND IONIZES THE GAS RESPONSIBLE FOR AGN EMISSION LINES. WE PROPOSE TO ADVANCE UNDERSTANDING OF THE X-RAY-TO-OPTICAL/UV SEDS OF THE MAJORITY POPULATION OF RADIO-QUIET AGNS OVER ALL THE OBSERVATIONALLY ACCESSIBLE PARTS OF THE LUMINOSITY-REDSHIFT PLANE. THIS WILL BE DONE BY COMBINING MODERN LARGE AGN SURVEYS, SUCH AS THE SLOAN DIGITAL SKY SURVEY AND DEEP-FIELD SURVEYS, WITH THE ENORMOUS DATA ARCHIVES FROM XMM-NEWTON, CHANDRA, ROSAT, SWIFT, SUZAKU, AND OTHER MISSIONS. WE WILL ALSO INCLUDE ARCHIVAL UV, OPTICAL, AND INFRARED PHOTOMETRIC INFORMATION FROM GALEX, THE UV/OPTICAL MONITORS ON XMM-NEWTON AND SWIFT, HST, UKIDSS, 2MASS, AND SPITZER IN OUR INVESTIGATIONS. OUR ANALYSES WILL ADDRESS SEVERAL TIGHTLY RELATED KEY QUESTIONS. WE WILL ASSESS WHAT PRACTICABLE OBSERVABLES OF AGN SEDS IN THE X-RAY-TO-OPTICAL/UV BANDPASS PROVIDE THE MOST INSIGHT INTO THEIR ACCRETION PROCESSES; SOME WIDELY USED OBSERVABLES AT PRESENT ARE LIKELY NOT OPTIMAL FOR ANSWERING RELEVANT PHYSICAL QUESTIONS. WE WILL CLARIFY THE NATURE OF THE LUMINOSITY, EDDINGTON FRACTION, SMBH MASS, AND REDSHIFT DEPENDENCES OF X-RAY-TO-OPTICAL/UV SEDS. CURRENT STUDIES OF THESE DEPENDENCES OFTEN SIGNIFICANTLY DISAGREE WITH EACH OTHER, MAKING IT DIFFICULT TO USE THE OBSERVATIONAL RESULTS TO GUIDE DEVELOPMENT OF PHYSICAL DISK-CORONA MODELS. THE CONTRADICTORY RESULTS APPEAR TO BE DUE TO UNRESOLVED SYSTEMATIC UNCERTAINTIES, AND THUS A CENTRAL ASPECT OF OUR WORK WILL BE THE REDUCTION AND REALISTIC QUANTIFICATION (VIA, E.G., MONTE CARLO SIMULATIONS) OF SYSTEMATICS INCLUDING LUMINOSITY DISPERSION, AGN MISCLASSIFICATION, DETECTION-FRACTION EFFECTS, ABSORPTION EFFECTS, HOST-GALAXY LIGHT CONTAMINATION, AND AGN VARIABILITY. VARIABILITY WILL BE STUDIED USING LARGE SAMPLES OF AGNS HAVING SIMULTANEOUS X-RAY-OPTICAL/UV DATA OR MULTIPLE X-RAY OBSERVATIONS. FINALLY, OUR ANALYSES WILL BE USED TO SET THE TIGHTEST CONSTRAINTS UPON THE UNIVERSALITY OF AGN X-RAY EMISSION AND THE ROBUSTNESS OF THE ACCRETION-DISK CORONA. THIS PROPOSAL IS DIRECTLY RELEVANT TO NASA STRATEGIC SUBGOAL 3D. IT WILL PROVIDE INSIGHT INTO PHENOMENA NEAR BLACK HOLES (OBJECTIVE 3D.1), AND IT WILL ADDRESS THE FORMATION AND EVOLUTION OF GALAXIES AND COSMIC STRUCTURES (OBJECTIVE 3D.2).
